About four years ago I made a little book for someone that I was in love with. I wrote down something like:\
\
"One day, the world will shatter into a billion tiny pieces and one of those pieces will be a fragment of this paper, that shows, not proves, that we created something as real as something could be\'94.\
\
I\'92m really happy to still be in love with that person. And perhaps in a bittersweet kind of way, I\'92m really happy that I still believe in what I wrote. I think that's why I\'92m here, writing into this near-certain void. Somewhere I still believe that we\'92re somehow eternal, even if all that\'92s left \'a0is a particle of bone dust flying through space. Somehow I believe that our moments of love and joy are deeply meaningful and inextricably tied with the fate of the universe \'96 however fleeting and small they may be. Is this a very hopeful thought? I think it\'92s also a very human thought.\
\
Humans are incredibly hopeful creatures. Maybe that\'92s going to be our downfall, that too many of us stayed hopeful about the way we were taught things are supposed to work when it was clearly destroying so much of what we love, when it was cancelling so many better, fairer futures that never ended up happening.\
\
This is a poem in Spanish and Dutch I wrote for a film I\'92m working on. It was a way of coming to terms with how my real, mortal, physical self was never going to live up to the idealised imaged I had constructed of myself. But in the film I also loosely related it to lost futures in general, especially in a time of political uncertainty.\
